text:
In the end, what we're trying to predict is the net effect of the actions of a bunch of individual actors -- the accounts on the exchange. If we had the private information of every account like e.g. the exchange has (trade history, currency balances, money transfers in and out of the account, *open positions*), that would surely be a tremendously powerful tool.
Since we can't have that, my main idea with the event stream was to partially deanonymize the account activities into e.g. a Bayesian inference model to 'learn' the hidden variables of the system. Instead of hard numbers, at least a hazy characterization of what groupings of actors with similar behaviors are doing, or will do, or would do in a hypothetical

text:
every time a trade occurs, it means a *position has been opened* by a single actor in the system, the buyer, who now holds an amount of bitcoin at a specific buy price. That actor is motivated to sell for a higher price than that.
So, if you knew the buy price and open time of the positions for an account, you would have a _very_ good idea what kinds of prices they would be interested in selling at, and when in the future they may or may not act on it.

text:
yeah, didn't really get anywhere.  Confirmed that: yes, the bitcoin trade seems to be markovian -- random walk.  Meaning: information about where it *is* is more important than any information about where it was.

Going to return to what I have done so far, reasonably ~ 60% odds of getting the sign right at, say 30-40 min in the future.   This is without setting up a holdout set (yet), but I have normalized everything, so that doesn't matter as much as it used to.

Next I'll work on the F-score and see how the predictor does at getting a good enough F-score.
